# Human-centered design

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Overview
Human-Centered Design (HCD) is a user-centered approach to problem-solving and solution development, focusing on understanding the needs, behaviors, and preferences of end-users.

## Purpose
The purpose of HCD is to develop innovative solutions that meet user needs and drive positive outcomes by fostering empathy for users, promoting creative thinking, and prioritizing user feedback throughout the design process.

## How it works
HCD involves a workshop-based process consisting of five steps: User Research and Understanding, Ideation and Concept Generation, Prototyping and Testing, Iteration and Improvement, and Evaluation and Implementation. This iterative approach enables R&D teams to refine solutions based on user input, leading to more user-centric final products or solutions.

## Requirements
To effectively use HCD for R&D purposes, deep listening, fast iteration, capacity to let go of ideas, stakeholders' participation, and fast prototyping skills are required.

## Reflections
When using HCD for R&D purposes, it is essential to prioritize the needs and experiences of end-users, foster multidisciplinary collaboration, and cultivate empathy for users. Additionally, embracing an iterative approach and understanding the context of users can lead to effective solution design.

## Related methods (if any)
HCD is related to Co-creation, Collective Intelligence, Human Centered Design, innovation challenges, and System Thinking.
